        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 5:6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", Hebrews The former passage almost settles the meaning here. Keil ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "assumes",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " that a mounted escort is meant], ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "and fifty men to run before him",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " [as Absalom before him (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Samuel 15:1",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). Adonijah seems in every way to have imitated Absalom. Josephus says he resembled him in disposition. Chariots, horses, and outrunners are mentioned (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Samuel 8:11",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") as the very first of the king's insigina. Horses were such natural and familiar tokens of royal state (not being employed in agriculture or for travelling), that the Hebrew kings were warned (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 17:16",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") against multiplying them. Outrunners again, such as the Roman emperors had (called by them ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "cursores",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), and such as we find at the present day in Egypt, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "footmen",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " who precede the chariot at full speed, and by their shrill cries clear the way, are admirably calculated to impress the public mind. According to Morier, \"runners before the king's horse in Persia are indispensable to the royal state.\" Adonijah hoped by this display of regal pomp to win the suffrages of the people.] 1 Kings 1:5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
